# SEO And AI Search Standards

- Treat SEO as a revenue and trust channel, not a traffic vanity metric.
- Keep site sections tightly focused by topic and intent; avoid mixing unrelated themes on the same page.

## Content Rules

- Make core facts easy to extract in short blocks: what the page/tool is, who it is for, pricing, key features, outputs, limits, and update date.
- Use one clear primary keyword plus natural secondary variants; write for humans first and avoid keyword stuffing.
- Use `<strong>` around critical facts that users and AI systems should reliably capture.
- Preserve heading hierarchy with one `h1`, then ordered `h2`/`h3` sections.
- Add FAQ-style content when it matches real user questions or objections.

## Metadata And Schema

- Give each indexable page a unique title, description, canonical URL, and Open Graph/Twitter metadata.
- Add applicable schema such as `WebApplication`, `Organization`, `FAQPage`, and `BreadcrumbList`.
- Keep brand facts consistent across metadata and page copy: organization name, offer, target users, and trust/contact signals.

## Freshness, Links, And Performance

- Refresh important SEO pages every 30-90 days when possible and surface `last-modified` data where useful.
- Use descriptive internal links to related tools, articles, and comparison pages to strengthen topical authority.
- Protect Core Web Vitals: target `TTFB < 200ms`, `LCP < 2.5s`, and `CLS < 0.1`; optimize images, preload critical assets, and lazy-load non-critical content.

## Example

```tsx
<section>
  <h2>Core Facts</h2>
  <p><strong>Free</strong> SVG to JSX converter for <strong>React</strong> and <strong>TypeScript</strong>.</p>
  <ul><li><strong>Input</strong>: SVG markup</li><li><strong>Output</strong>: JSX component</li></ul>
</section>
```

- Favor clarity, factual density, and brand consistency over clever copy.
